  "texts": [
    "Some philosophers think of this kind of norm-guided teleology as an essential and irreducible feature of human cognition.",
    "It is an essential feature if nothing could have the kind of cognition we have without being answerable to these norms and meeting them (enough of the time) for the normatively right reasons (i.e., non-accidentally); it is an irreducible feature if there is no way to characterise the norms and the goals whose fulfilment they constrain except in terms that presuppose the norms themselves.",
    "The normativity of cognition could not be explained in terms of more fundamental notions like biological function, for example.",
    "By contrast, norms of practical rationality and the goals they serve are non-essential features if it turns out to be a merely descriptive fact that humans tend to respect or approximate them; they are reducible features if this descriptive fact can be explained in more fundamental terms.",
    "I take debates about reducibility and essentialness to be independent of the question whether the broad norms-and-teleology approach to characterising cognition outlined above is correct."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}